            <!-- Theory & explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Neutron activation basics</h2>
              <p>
                Neutron activation occurs when a stable nucleus captures a
                neutron and becomes a radioactive isotope. In neutron activation
                analysis (NAA), a sample is irradiated in a neutron field
                (typically a research reactor), producing radionuclides that
                emit characteristic gamma rays. Measuring these gamma rays
                allows you to determine the elemental composition and
                concentration.
              </p>

              <h3>Core activation equation</h3>
              <p>
                For a single target isotope with constant neutron flux and a
                single dominant reaction channel, the activity at the end of
                irradiation is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( A_{\text{EOI}} = N \,\sigma\, \phi \,\bigl(1 - e^{-\lambda
                t_{\text{irr}}}\bigr) \)
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>\(N\): number of target atoms in the sample</li>
                <li>\(\sigma\): microscopic cross-section (cm²)</li>
                <li>\(\phi\): neutron flux (n/cm²·s)</li>
                <li>\(\lambda = \ln 2 / T_{1/2}\): decay constant (1/s)</li>
                <li>\(t_{\text{irr}}\): irradiation time (s)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The saturation activity is reached for very long irradiations:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( A_{\text{sat}} = N \,\sigma\, \phi \)
              </div>

              <h3>Number of target atoms</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator converts sample mass to the number of target
                atoms using:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( N = \dfrac{m \, f}{A} \, N_A \)</div>
              <ul>
                <li>\(m\): sample mass (g)</li>
                <li>
                  \(f\): isotopic abundance (fraction of the target isotope)
                </li>
                <li>\(A\): atomic mass (g/mol)</li>
                <li>\(N_A = 6.022\times10^{23}\): Avogadro’s number</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Decay during cooling and counting</h3>
              <p>
                After the irradiation stops, activity decays exponentially. At
                the start of counting after a cooling time \(t_{\text{cool}}\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( A_{\text{start}} = A_{\text{EOI}} \, e^{-\lambda
                t_{\text{cool}}} \)
              </div>
              <p>
                During counting, activity continues to decrease. The average
                activity over a counting time \(t_{\text{count}}\) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( A_{\text{avg}} = \dfrac{A_{\text{start}}}{\lambda
                t_{\text{count}}} \bigl(1 - e^{-\lambda t_{\text{count}}}\bigr)
                \)
              </div>

              <h3>Expected counts and detection limit</h3>
              <p>
                If you provide detector efficiency \(\varepsilon\) and gamma
                emission probability \(P_\gamma\), the expected number of counts
                in the full-energy peak is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( C = A_{\text{avg}} \, \varepsilon \, P_\gamma \,
                t_{\text{count}} \)
              </div>
              <p>
                Given a minimum detectable count rate \(R_{\min}\) (counts per
                second), the minimum detectable activity (MDA) at the start of
                counting is approximated by:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{MDA} \approx \dfrac{R_{\min}}{\varepsilon \, P_\gamma}
                \)
              </div>
              <p>
                The corresponding minimum detectable mass of the target element
                is then:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( m_{\min} = \dfrac{\text{MDA}}{\sigma \phi \bigl(1 -
                e^{-\lambda t_{\text{irr}}}\bigr) e^{-\lambda t_{\text{cool}}}}
                \cdot \dfrac{A}{N_A f} \)
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                This assumes the same irradiation and cooling conditions you
                entered and ignores self-shielding, competing reactions, and
                matrix effects.
              </p>

              <h2>Assumptions and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Single target isotope and single reaction channel (no burn-up
                  or competing reactions).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Constant neutron flux and cross-section (no spectral changes
                  or self-shielding).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Homogeneous sample; geometry effects on efficiency are
                  captured only via the efficiency input.
                </li>
                <li>
                  No background subtraction or statistical treatment of
                  detection limits (simple cps threshold).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For rigorous NAA, reactor dosimetry, or safety-critical work,
                use validated activation codes and follow institutional and
                regulatory procedures.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How accurate is this neutron activation calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                The tool implements the standard analytical activation and decay
                equations and is numerically accurate for the given inputs.
                However, real experiments often deviate from the ideal
                assumptions (flux gradients, self-shielding, multiple reaction
                channels, background, dead time, etc.), so results should be
                treated as order-of-magnitude estimates or for planning
                purposes.
              </p>

              <h3>What cross-section value should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                Use a thermal or effective cross-section appropriate for your
                neutron spectrum, typically taken from evaluated nuclear data
                libraries (e.g., ENDF, JEFF, JENDL). For reactor NAA, many labs
                publish recommended effective cross-sections for common monitor
                and analytical isotopes.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I model multiple isotopes or reaction channels?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on a single target–product pair. For
                multi-element samples or cases with significant burn-up or
                branching, you need more advanced activation codes that solve
                coupled differential equations for nuclide chains.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I choose the minimum detectable count rate?</h3>
              <p>
                A rough rule of thumb is to use a count rate corresponding to a
                few tens of counts over the counting period, depending on
                background and required confidence level. Many labs use formal
                Currie detection limit calculations; you can convert that to an
                equivalent cps and enter it here.
              </p>
            </section>
